            Hint
**********************************************-->


<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
  <p><term>Odd functions</term> have the following property:
  <me>f(x) = -f(-x)</me>
  </p>
  <p>You can overlay the graph of <m>f(x)</m> with <m>-f(-x)</m> to informally check if a function is odd. You can also compare the two functions algebraically.</p>
  <p>The graph below illustrates that the given function, <m>f(x) = $f</m>, is an <alert>odd</alert> function.</p>
  <graph copySource="g1">
    <function name="solF" copySource="fL"/>
    <booleanInput name="showAlt" anchor="(-2,1)" prefill="true">
      <label>Show <m>-f(-x)</m></label>
    </booleanInput>
    <function name="altFL" domain="(-infinity, 0)" styleNumber="8" hide="!$showAlt">-$$f(-x)</function>
    <function name="altFR" domain="(0, infinity)" styleNumber="8" hide="!$showAlt">-$$f(-x)</function>
    <legend>
      <label forObject="altFL"><math simplify="numberspreserveorder">-$$f(-x)</math></label>
      <label forObject="solF"><m>$f</m></label>
    </legend>
  </graph>
</solution>
</problem>



